WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.680
Hey there, welcome to the Posit Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:22.040
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:27.280
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.320
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:43.160
Can't wait to see you there. So today I am super excited to introduce Tom Grace and Darren

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:52.200
Cope from HMRC. Let's start with Tom. Tom, I would love it if you could introduce yourself,

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:57.799
tell us a little bit about your role, and maybe a little bit about HMRC in general.

00:00:57.799 --> 00:01:05.320
Okay, hello. So yeah, I'm Tom. HMRC, for those who are unfamiliar or from outside of the

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:14.559
UK, is the tax office. My role is as a tech lead on the Posit platform team. So what we

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:22.099
do is we build the Posit installations. We have about seven or eight of those now of

00:01:22.099 --> 00:01:26.919
Workbench and Connect. We build those, and we make sure that they are shaped the right

00:01:26.919 --> 00:01:33.919
way so that the data scientists across the organisation can do the best work they can.

00:01:33.919 --> 00:01:41.199
The tech lead thing is it's partly technical, but it's also quite heavy on the culture aspect

00:01:41.199 --> 00:01:48.519
of leadership. So it's making sure that our team is a good team to be on, and also making

00:01:48.519 --> 00:01:54.120
sure that we are approachable and can be, and find it easy to be empathetic with those

00:01:54.120 --> 00:02:01.919
who are using the platforms and systems that we build to win. That's broadly, that's my

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:10.360
role within the broader picture of it. I can explain a bit more about HMRC if you need.

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:15.399
You've got some pretty big datasets, jumped across quite a lot of different things.

00:02:15.399 --> 00:02:19.800
I think that the coolest thing that you said in that whole thing was that you have a Posit

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:25.300
platform team, which means you have a team of people dedicated to making sure that people

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:30.199
can use the tools that you have and know how to use them. You can use them effectively.

00:02:30.199 --> 00:02:36.119
I think that that's really rare and kind of amazing because I can hear from people in

00:02:36.119 --> 00:02:44.759
the chat, I'm sure all the time, that we get tools from vendors, from suppliers, and

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:48.800
then they kind of come to our organization and die out. Nobody knows how to use them.

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:52.440
They're not very well supported. It really takes an internal effort to make sure that

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:57.839
that happens. And it sounds like you all do that in a wonderful way. Well, I want to invite

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:05.839
Darren to tell us a little bit about his role at HMRC or give us some extra context

00:03:05.839 --> 00:03:12.839
on HMRC. Darren, are you with us? There he is.

00:03:12.839 --> 00:03:16.839
Can you hear me?

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:19.839
Yes, we can hear you.

00:03:19.839 --> 00:03:26.839
Oh my God, it works. I am on my phone. How thoroughly modern. All the devices fail me.

00:03:26.839 --> 00:03:31.839
All right, I can hear you now. Yes, I can. For a little bit it was ringing, but you're good now.

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:36.839
Oh, hooray, hooray. This is the wonders of working in the office. Tom has fortunately

00:03:36.839 --> 00:03:40.839
worked from home and so has wonderful Wi-Fi.

00:03:40.839 --> 00:03:45.839
Uh-oh. I think that we lost him.

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:46.839
Oh, am I breaking up?

00:03:46.839 --> 00:03:48.839
Yep, just a little bit.

00:03:48.839 --> 00:03:54.839
Oh no, no, I had to stand next to the window. Well, concentrate on Tom. We'll see how we get on.

00:03:54.839 --> 00:03:57.839
Would you like me to do a quick introduction of Darren?

00:03:57.839 --> 00:04:04.839
I was going to say that would be fantastic because I know that Darren is a POSIT subject matter expert, which is a very unique role.

00:04:04.839 --> 00:04:13.839
I'm not sure I know any other POSIT subject matter experts at other organisations. Tom, what is Darren's role on the team?

00:04:13.839 --> 00:04:22.839
So Darren is part of, he sits between the platform team and also our fairly new POSIT adoption team.

00:04:22.839 --> 00:04:31.839
And it's his job to understand the nuts and bolts of what it is people need to do on the platform.

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:37.839
So the platform team themselves are coming at it from the perspective of, oh, we've got some servers over here.

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:41.839
And Darren's coming at it from the perspective of I've got some data sets.

00:04:41.839 --> 00:04:46.839
How do I get access to those? What do I want to do with them?

00:04:46.839 --> 00:04:51.839
What kind of problems are coming down the track? How can we use this better?

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:57.839
Are there situations where people are using legacy tooling at the moment where with a bit of support,

00:04:57.839 --> 00:05:01.839
they could move across to something that's a bit more modern and easier to work with?

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:11.839
So it's a greater focus on user need rather than the technical aspect of it.

00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:17.839
Spending a bit of time trying out, like kicking the tyres on the AI functionality,

00:05:17.839 --> 00:05:27.839
playing with new tools and approaches and just building a bit of an understanding and relationship with people from that end.

00:05:27.839 --> 00:05:31.839
Right. One thing I heard from Darren was that when I talked to him earlier this week,

00:05:31.839 --> 00:05:38.839
he said, I just came out of a coffee and coding session for people who want to use POSIT tools and have never used them before.

00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:43.839
And he had over 160 people in there, which is wild.

00:05:43.839 --> 00:05:47.839
That's that's as many people as we have on the hangout call right now. Right.

00:05:47.839 --> 00:05:53.839
So all those people from your organization who are interested in using different tools,

00:05:53.839 --> 00:06:00.839
who get the chance to have an empathetic person sitting there and saying, like, let me just walk you through how this works.

00:06:00.839 --> 00:06:02.839
Let me show you what this is like.

00:06:02.839 --> 00:06:09.839
And I know that a lot of the people at your organization who are interested in using these tools are coming from other things like SAS.

00:06:09.839 --> 00:06:14.839
Do you still have like a whole lot of SAS users inside of your org?

00:06:14.839 --> 00:06:22.839
Yes. I mean, it's a very large organization. We pretty much we've got a whole number of everything users.

00:06:22.839 --> 00:06:28.839
There's a fair number of SAS users. There's, as you'd expect, shed loads of Excel users.

00:06:28.839 --> 00:06:34.839
But probably pretty much any large enterprise tool that you can think of.

00:06:34.839 --> 00:06:45.839
There's a fair few users of that. There are people who are perhaps multi-decade SAS users who would be interested in moving across.

00:06:45.839 --> 00:06:49.839
But it's quite a it's quite a learn learning curve for them.

00:06:49.839 --> 00:06:56.839
It is. Yeah. I really love the way that you all approach it with lots of empathy and and kindness and stuff.

00:06:56.839 --> 00:07:00.839
And Darren also mentioned doing roadshows to other teams.

00:07:00.839 --> 00:07:08.839
So like going into other teams and saying, hey, it seems like maybe you all would like to move to open source tool solutions here.

00:07:08.839 --> 00:07:15.839
Let me show you what this can do, which is, I also think, a really, really unique thing inside of the organization.

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:23.839
OK, well, let's pivot just a little bit so that I can backtrack slightly and ask another context building question,

00:07:23.839 --> 00:07:29.839
which is about the tools that you all use, the problems that you face and the kinds of data that you see.

00:07:29.839 --> 00:07:36.839
So for people who are not in a tax focused area and maybe don't have the experience of that,

00:07:36.839 --> 00:07:46.839
could you tell us a little bit about maybe an example of a type of problem you tackle, the type of data that you see in the tools you use?

00:07:47.839 --> 00:07:53.839
Or that your teams use that you support? Yes. Yeah. So, yeah, I don't do any data analysis myself,

00:07:53.839 --> 00:08:02.839
but it's the organization covers everything from things like import and export duty.

00:08:03.839 --> 00:08:14.839
So there are teams who are doing things like running analysis on bulk corporate,

00:08:14.839 --> 00:08:20.839
like corporate returns, or they are looking back at the historical data, looking for patterns.

00:08:20.839 --> 00:08:34.840
There are teams who are modeling proposals for the government around, you know, if we introduce this, what might that do?

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:40.840
There are teams who are doing things like looking for the logo on the Internet.

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:47.840
There are teams doing loads and loads of different things, and it is a huge gulf of different.

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:57.840
It's a huge gulf of different things, but we have using just POSIT, I think we are edging towards about 600 analysts

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:06.840
and they are in a huge variety of areas and also experience levels or kind of focus areas.

00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:16.840
So there are people who are doing, who are building tooling to use AI models to expose internal documentation better.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:25.840
But there are also people who are just doing kind of routine, almost like an enhanced spreadsheet type work.

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:33.840
It's a huge breadth of things. It's massive, the scope sideways of it.

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:38.840
But I'm not super close to the day to day of what people are doing.

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:44.840
They come when there is a problem shaped like, I wish this machine was bigger.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:50.840
Well, that's what I would love to ask you about, too. When you say POSIT, like we use POSIT as a tool,

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:54.840
POSIT is also this like multifaceted thing with all these different things inside of it.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:59.840
Do you have a lot of R users who are in RStudio or Positron?

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:03.840
Do you have a lot of Python users who are in Positron?

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:11.840
What does that sort of composition look like for you as far as the people that you're serving?

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:18.840
It varies a bit between teams. I think we're about 50-50 between or maybe slightly under 50-50.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:22.840
Slightly fewer R users than Python users.

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:29.840
And the Python users are mostly between Positron and VS Code, gradually going more Positron.

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:37.840
We have got some people using Jupyter still. And we try and support just whatever tools work best for people.

00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:42.840
So we try as hard as we can not to push people in a particular direction,

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:52.840
but to make available the things that are right for their use case and to talk to them about why a certain thing is easy or hard.

00:10:52.840 --> 00:11:00.840
In terms of things deployed to Connect, the majority these days are Python.

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:09.840
I think the future for Connect apps seems like it's quite heavy on Python, at least for the more sort of trailblazing type stuff.

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:13.840
But we've got plenty of Shiny and plenty of R as well.

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:18.840
So when you say Python, is that more like Streamlit apps being launched in Connect?

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:19.840
Yes.

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:20.840
Streamlit, OK.

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:21.840
Yeah.

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:25.840
Very cool. So we've got Streamlit, we've got Shiny, we've got deployment on Connect.

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:32.840
We have got a really cool split of R and Python users, which I feel like I also don't hear very often.

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:33.840
I think that's very cool.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:37.840
And it leads me to an anonymous question that we have in Slido.

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:39.840
Let me go highlight it.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:40.840
We'll send it to the top.

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:44.840
And don't forget, you can go upvote questions if you see any that you like, everybody.

00:11:44.840 --> 00:11:51.840
This question says, when people suggest new tools that they want to use, what is the most helpful information that they share?

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:53.840
How does that process go?

00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:59.840
This says, in short, can you help teach us how to get things approved by our own teams?

00:12:03.840 --> 00:12:14.840
The way we tend to work, if people come and say, if I take a simple example, like an extension to Positron, which is pretty easy for us to do,

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:22.840
the main questions we'd have is, what's the licensing like?

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:28.840
What's the support and how actively maintained is it?

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:36.840
And is it solving a unique problem that is not solved by something else that's already available?

00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:39.840
So something like that is quite simple for us to do.

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:52.840
The main reason we don't just blanket allow VS Code extensions is we need to make sure we keep them maintained for the foreseeable future so that we don't pull the rug on anybody.

00:12:52.840 --> 00:13:02.840
For more significant kind of technologies, say if we were introducing Connect now as new.

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:03.840
Pretty big.

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:06.840
Yeah, something big like that.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:14.840
The main thing is, what does this give that what you have available now does not provide?

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:18.840
Is this, what can you do now?

00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:24.840
Can you build an EC2 server and stick your Python app on it?

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:25.840
Why isn't that good enough?

00:13:25.840 --> 00:13:31.840
What's it bringing that what you have available can't provide now?

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:42.840
And the way we work, the amount of evidence increases with how complex that piece of work is.

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:55.840
So an example where we didn't implement it was looking at the inference servers for some of the self-hosted AI models.

00:13:55.840 --> 00:14:03.840
We were experimenting with those early on before we had access to models provided by cloud providers.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:10.840
And playing with those, we did experiment with whether we would benefit from the inference server.

00:14:10.840 --> 00:14:13.840
There were some costs, there were some complexities.

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:17.840
There is business approval and support type stuff.

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:20.840
And that's quite a high bar.

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:25.840
So the effort needs to be worth it.

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:36.840
And I think the thing where there's maybe a gap sometimes is when people are asking about new things.

00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:41.840
They're seeing it in a, I can grab this on my laptop at home.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:46.840
I can make it available. And if I get bored of it in six months, I can get rid of it.

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:55.840
Where for quite a few larger organizations in particular, they're looking at it and going, as soon as you put that there, we're running it for 10 years.

00:14:55.840 --> 00:15:00.840
That is going to be used by someone and we're going to have to maintain it.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:03.840
Right. Someone's going to have to keep it clean.

00:15:03.840 --> 00:15:07.840
Yeah, it's going to have to keep working for a long time.

00:15:07.840 --> 00:15:10.840
We do that even with the VS Code extensions.

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:13.840
We're expecting that we will have to keep these available.

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:18.840
And so we do make more of a hurdle to bringing them on.

00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:21.840
Just because we don't want to pull things away from people later.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:26.840
Right. Yes. Yeah. I think that the bigger your organization gets, the harder that process gets.

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:30.840
And it's understandable with that kind of scale.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:41.840
I wanted to go back to something you said about like, you know, could you just spin up an EC2 server and stick this on there and would that suffice?

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:51.840
That reminds me that you all have some dynamic allocation happening where you are allowing people to sort of choose their own compute and giving them budgets.

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:55.840
And I had forgotten about that. I'd love you to talk about that just a little bit.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:59.840
So people have some context around that as well.

00:15:59.840 --> 00:16:01.840
Because I think it's very cool.

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:04.840
So, yeah, that's that's been very popular with people.

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:09.840
So that's the thing that we did a small scale rollout of sometime last year.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:13.840
And it's getting gradually getting more adoption now.

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:21.840
It's kind of built on it. Well, it's built on top of the Slurm launcher inside Workbench.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:34.840
And what we've done is configured that in such a way that instead of having a static Slurm cluster and slotting things onto it, we launch EC2 instances as people request them.

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:44.840
But the thing that's been very popular is in the dropdown, you have a list of instance types and it has the price per hour in dollars.

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:49.840
And so an analyst can be given a monthly or project budget.

00:16:49.840 --> 00:17:00.840
They might choose to use that running a couple of different small instances for a couple of months, or they might choose to run a huge instance for a day.

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:04.839
But it puts it empowers them to make those decisions.

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:09.839
And we've built it in such a way that we can sort of follow the org chart.

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:20.839
So the senior management can set the overall budget and then team leads can be delegated down to and pass that out as appropriate.

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:24.839
And that has been incredibly popular.

00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:33.839
The initial use case was people who needed to do some particularly large processing on an occasional sort of schedule.

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:43.839
And that sort of model is difficult to do with the way large organization budgets are set.

00:17:43.839 --> 00:17:52.839
But using knowledge of how the organization thinks about budgets, we built a thing where they can go, OK, allocate this much money.

00:17:52.839 --> 00:18:03.839
That's your pot for the year. Once it's gone, it's gone, which fits the budget cycle and can be then they can use it dynamically as they need.

00:18:03.839 --> 00:18:06.839
And that's that's been very popular.

00:18:06.839 --> 00:18:11.839
That's awesome. I feel like I mentioned earlier, we don't get to hear IT perspectives a lot.

00:18:11.839 --> 00:18:16.839
And I have a couple of questions that are kind of along that sort of tack.

00:18:16.839 --> 00:18:21.839
So I would love to hop over to Slido and ask some of those.

00:18:21.839 --> 00:18:28.839
Natasha had asked. Let's see. Natasha had asked one.

00:18:28.839 --> 00:18:35.839
And then there is also an anonymous one. Aha.

00:18:35.839 --> 00:18:43.839
Here we go. We have an anonymous question that says, how do I find time for data science training if I'm struggling to complete routine work?

00:18:43.839 --> 00:18:49.839
Oh, no, it's gone. OK, somebody somebody press something in Slido.

00:18:49.839 --> 00:18:54.839
It's OK. It was at the bottom and it jumped to the top.

00:18:54.839 --> 00:19:01.839
It says, how do I find time for data science training if I'm struggling to complete routine work tasks?

00:19:01.839 --> 00:19:05.839
I am IT and I run a Posit Connect platform.

00:19:05.839 --> 00:19:13.839
So this is an IT perspective, trying to keep track of business as usual, but also trying to make time for data science training.

00:19:13.839 --> 00:19:25.839
Tom, do you all inside of your sort of admin or IT focus organization train in data science yourselves and try to keep up with what your end users are doing?

00:19:25.839 --> 00:19:33.839
We we don't train formally, but as a team, we we have a system of dogfooding.

00:19:33.839 --> 00:19:43.839
So if we've got. So we have our own tiny Posit Connect tenancy that we use for our own purposes.

00:19:43.839 --> 00:19:49.839
And what we do is we use the tools that we manage to build internal things like dashboards.

00:19:49.839 --> 00:19:55.839
So we have things like a release dashboard so people can see changes to the platform over time.

00:19:55.839 --> 00:20:06.839
We build those things on top of Connect. We use it to do ad hoc analysis type things as we need to.

00:20:06.839 --> 00:20:16.839
So we sort of bake it into our daily work. And maybe we try and budget in that.

00:20:16.839 --> 00:20:22.839
It's valuable in and of itself to do things like that as part of the team culture.

00:20:22.839 --> 00:20:26.839
We make sure that we don't overcommit as a team.

00:20:26.839 --> 00:20:34.839
And so we make sure that we have enough time. So it's acceptable for someone to.

00:20:34.839 --> 00:20:41.839
For example, instead of analyzing how long it took to do some tickets in Excel where it's familiar,

00:20:41.839 --> 00:20:50.839
actually taking 10 times longer and doing it in Python or R in order to become familiar with those tools is an acceptable thing to do.

00:20:50.839 --> 00:20:55.839
There have been a few examples where there would be something that we could do very quickly,

00:20:55.839 --> 00:20:59.839
where people just use the tools they already know, smash the thing out.

00:20:59.839 --> 00:21:07.839
But we've managed, we've structured the team in such a way that actually you can implicitly train.

00:21:07.839 --> 00:21:11.839
I don't know how we'd do it if it was formalized training.

00:21:11.839 --> 00:21:17.839
That might be more of a commitment, but making a bit of space in there to work like that.

00:21:17.839 --> 00:21:21.839
It's the way we try and structure the team as best we can.

00:21:21.839 --> 00:21:26.839
I think that that is a very brave answer because, oh, my gosh, when I'm looking at something and I'm like, I have to get this done.

00:21:26.839 --> 00:21:34.839
And I know that I could learn something new by going the long way and using something different.

00:21:34.839 --> 00:21:37.839
I really struggle with that. I just think, oh, no, I just have to get this done.

00:21:37.839 --> 00:21:40.839
I've got to do it the way that I know. So that's wonderful advice.

00:21:40.839 --> 00:21:43.839
And I think it's so difficult to actually take.

00:21:44.839 --> 00:21:49.839
It's difficult to do as an individual contributor.

00:21:49.839 --> 00:21:58.839
It needs to be an intentional feature of the team and an accepted thing, I think, by everyone involved.

