00:22:28.839 --> 00:22:36.839
She says, I noticed that when someone uses programming languages that no one else at the company uses, there can be difficulties when they leave.

00:22:36.839 --> 00:22:44.839
Either their work needs to be converted to another language or a new person needs to be hired who can use that different languages as it is.

00:22:44.839 --> 00:22:50.839
How do you minimize this issue? Do you have any sort of thoughts on this from your perspective?

00:22:52.839 --> 00:23:02.839
At the organization level, it's it's so big that we sort of don't end up with that problem within the team because we're a relatively small team.

00:23:02.839 --> 00:23:08.839
So we are there's five of us pretty much.

00:23:08.839 --> 00:23:14.839
Well, give or take. What we would tend to do is we try and minimize it.

00:23:14.839 --> 00:23:26.839
And I think similar to when introducing a new tool, a similar approach of really justify why you need to bring it on.

00:23:26.839 --> 00:23:32.839
If it is worth bringing on that new tool, it needs to be more than just a personal preference.

00:23:32.839 --> 00:23:37.839
So we use a lot of Ansible for things. It's not something I like very much.

00:23:37.839 --> 00:23:47.839
Not a fan of Ansible, but still using it because it's in wide use across the team and the wider team and is unlikely to go anywhere.

00:23:48.839 --> 00:23:57.839
So at that side, try and avoid that problem. If it is worth bringing in, then try and make sure you're sharing work.

00:23:57.839 --> 00:24:05.839
So something we do within the team is similar to the making the doing it the slow way to learn more things.

00:24:05.839 --> 00:24:14.839
We try and have people who are less experienced take on areas of the system that they haven't used much before.

00:24:14.839 --> 00:24:24.839
Again, it's a little bit slower, but we try and avoid having the issue where this person specializes in this area.

00:24:24.839 --> 00:24:28.839
We still, as you'd expect, we still get things where someone is very familiar.

00:24:28.839 --> 00:24:33.839
And so we would lean on them if something especially unusual happens.

00:24:33.839 --> 00:24:41.839
But we will try and spread work around so that people do pick up that language that only one person uses.

00:24:41.839 --> 00:24:53.839
And even if it is slower, it tends to be valuable because I think every every language has its own quirks and good sides, bad sides.

00:24:53.839 --> 00:25:02.839
And I think for anyone who writes code, learning to write another language makes you better at the one you knew before, as well as teaching you about the other one.

00:25:02.839 --> 00:25:16.839
So if you mostly write R, spending a few weeks being annoyed at Python or vice versa, you'll be you see new patterns, new approaches, and you will learn something from it.

00:25:16.839 --> 00:25:20.839
It's it's not just a time sink.

00:25:20.839 --> 00:25:30.839
Yes, and I wanted to highlight a couple of really great things in the chat because they sort of touch on this and are great examples of what other people do.

00:25:30.839 --> 00:25:34.839
