00:29:37.839 --> 00:29:43.839
Could you give us an example of what large processing means for your team on the regular?

00:29:43.839 --> 00:29:45.839
So is that high input output?

00:29:45.839 --> 00:29:47.839
Is it high memory usage?

00:29:47.839 --> 00:29:54.839
Or is it just massive raw data that you're trying to funnel into a process and get some meaningful output from?

00:29:55.839 --> 00:30:06.839
The things we've seen so far are shaped like I need loads and loads of RAM and quite a lot of CPU on a single machine is the kind of use case we've seen so far.

00:30:06.839 --> 00:30:21.839
So that's what brought about the SLURM based use case is people saying, actually, I want a machine with half a terabyte of RAM and I want it for a week to do this piece of work.

00:30:21.839 --> 00:30:25.839
We don't or at least not within our space.

00:30:25.839 --> 00:30:34.839
We don't have anything that works well at the moment for a like an ad hoc bulk processing type thing.

00:30:34.839 --> 00:30:39.839
And we may want to get something with that later.

00:30:39.839 --> 00:30:47.839
But, yeah, large scale tends to be if it's ad hoc, I want a single giant machine.

00:30:48.839 --> 00:30:53.839
There are other systems dotted around that do more batch type stuff.

00:30:53.839 --> 00:31:08.839
But the users of POSIT tend to be consumers of the outputs of those systems rather than actually doing a raw processing job on all of this type stuff.

00:31:08.839 --> 00:31:10.839
So, yeah, that's roughly what big means.

00:31:10.839 --> 00:31:14.839
There is some stuff as well using multiple GPUs for a few different bits of pieces.

00:31:14.839 --> 00:31:19.839
So there's some GPU shaped stuff. There's some memory stuff.

00:31:19.839 --> 00:31:25.839
I haven't seen any requests for giant IO type stuff as yet.

00:31:25.839 --> 00:31:29.839
But, yeah, it tends to be memory for the most part.

