00:35:08.454 --> 00:35:19.415
Okay, let's see. We had a question that was more about upgrading. There it is. Okay,

00:35:20.055 --> 00:35:25.095
how often do you get to upgrade your Posit environment to bring in new packages, features,

00:35:25.095 --> 00:35:30.214
etc.? I like this question because you had mentioned people requesting things like extensions

00:35:30.214 --> 00:35:37.495
and Positron. When someone wants to use a package or a new tool, do you have a process that they

00:35:37.495 --> 00:35:44.294
have to go through to get packages approved and then also versions of R and Python?

00:35:46.135 --> 00:35:53.735
So packages as in like CRAN packages and Python packages, I'm assuming. Probably.

00:35:54.695 --> 00:36:02.455
So we make those available via package manager and then we have a facility where the individual

00:36:02.455 --> 00:36:09.174
teams are able to configure allow lists if they want to. So we would make PyPy available with

00:36:10.695 --> 00:36:17.254
standard scanning stuff like x-ray, filtering out anything that's particularly malicious.

00:36:17.814 --> 00:36:22.855
But then we have a facility where teams can configure their own allow lists by providing

00:36:22.855 --> 00:36:28.614
a list of packages and then they can have a filtered view of package manager. And some do

00:36:28.614 --> 00:36:33.974
that for safety reasons and some do it just so they don't get a sprawl of slightly different

00:36:33.974 --> 00:36:43.655
implementations. When it comes to anything that would require an OS package, that we would roll

00:36:43.655 --> 00:36:54.374
it into our standard release cycle. The way we do releases is we build everything into Docker

00:36:54.374 --> 00:37:01.495
images just as a convenient deployment artifact. In our development environment, we build several

00:37:01.495 --> 00:37:07.655
new versions per day and that gets rolled out to dev maybe once to three times a day.

00:37:08.614 --> 00:37:14.374
Any change like adding a new package just goes through that process and then we apply updated

00:37:14.374 --> 00:37:21.415
versions to each of our production tenancies on a for the most part monthly basis. But some of our

00:37:21.415 --> 00:37:30.855
more trailblazing people do every two weeks. We pull in new versions of Posit roughly a week after

00:37:30.855 --> 00:37:36.215
release for the most part. But for people who want to try things that are a bit newer, we also have

00:37:37.014 --> 00:37:43.974
an environment that runs the daily builds of Workbench so that when we're chatting to our

00:37:43.974 --> 00:37:48.374
friends in the kind of account and tech team, if they're telling us about shiny new things,

00:37:48.374 --> 00:37:55.575
we can just open it and go, I don't like the shade of that. So, yeah, we have the daily

00:37:55.575 --> 00:38:04.454
builds available as a test environment for our users as well. And we have it's all quite open.

00:38:04.534 --> 00:38:09.974
So, our end users have access to our source code repositories. Some of them have made changes.

00:38:12.534 --> 00:38:20.055
And, yeah, so, it's not crazy fast, but we can roll a new version out probably within about a

00:38:20.055 --> 00:38:26.614
month of release to everybody. I would love to ask a little bit about how you communicate those

00:38:26.614 --> 00:38:31.574
changes with people across the organization. Do you have a rolling newsletter that goes out by

00:38:31.574 --> 00:38:37.975
email? Do you have a Teams channel where all of those updates are mentioned? Or do people get a

00:38:37.975 --> 00:38:42.055
popup on their computer system that's like, hello, you have a new version, and this is what's

00:38:42.055 --> 00:38:52.375
different? So, we tell people via a Teams channel that updates are coming. And we have prearranged

00:38:52.375 --> 00:38:58.694
maintenance windows for each of the tenancies that align with what their priorities are. So,

00:38:59.655 --> 00:39:06.215
there's an agreed it's kind of off the form the third Thursday of the month type schedule.

00:39:08.055 --> 00:39:16.854
But also, we have kind of particularly engaged people from the Teams. So, the more trailblazer

00:39:16.854 --> 00:39:24.055
users or the senior kind of senior not quite manager, but the more senior people, they come

00:39:24.055 --> 00:39:32.134
to our planning sessions and stand-up sessions. So, people are aware of upcoming changes at the

00:39:32.134 --> 00:39:38.215
point where we're discussing what we're going to do, and they will have feedback at that point.

00:39:39.174 --> 00:39:40.134
Ah, before they come out.

00:39:40.134 --> 00:39:50.854
Often, yeah. So, people will be talking to us about, yeah, things, you know. Often requests or

00:39:51.655 --> 00:39:57.734
anything other than posit updates, usually those changes, they have come from users

00:39:57.734 --> 00:40:04.294
directly logging JIRA tickets, then coming to our planning and discussing where they should be in

00:40:04.294 --> 00:40:11.894
terms of priority, how broadly applicable those are, how soon they want them, that kind of thing.

00:40:13.174 --> 00:40:19.174
Fantastic. Yeah, you have much more communication than I have experienced in a lot of places around

00:40:19.174 --> 00:40:23.734
what's happening and why and getting sort of a roundup of feedback, which is, I think,

00:40:24.454 --> 00:40:30.535
amazing. I keep wondering, I wonder if Tom and Darian know how unique the HMRC is in this aspect,

00:40:30.535 --> 00:40:35.174
because it's just something I haven't seen in a lot of other places. Okay.

00:40:35.174 --> 00:40:38.935
We do try and be very close to our users, and that is.

00:40:39.495 --> 00:40:40.215
That's amazing.

00:40:40.215 --> 00:40:47.255
It's not just the formal things like planning. So, we have Teams channels that are for questions and

00:40:47.335 --> 00:40:56.694
support, and partly those are team specific, and they are for both things like what our library

00:40:56.694 --> 00:41:01.495
would you recommend for this use case, and then people kind of self-answer for what suits their

00:41:01.495 --> 00:41:08.775
team. We as the platform team sit in those channels and we'll jump, we'll see if people

00:41:08.775 --> 00:41:14.055
are having challenges with things, and quite often what we might do is just give them a call and

00:41:15.014 --> 00:41:22.134
watch someone struggle with however it is they're doing things, and then that might be,

00:41:23.014 --> 00:41:28.055
oh, we could use some help here, or we need to make a change to make it harder for this error

00:41:28.055 --> 00:41:29.574
to happen. Right.

00:41:31.014 --> 00:41:36.454
And actually seeing how people use it, we've learned a lot more about how the system should be,

00:41:37.414 --> 00:41:44.454
because we're approaching it from system administrator perspective, rather than

00:41:46.454 --> 00:41:48.215
people who are doing data science things.

00:41:50.694 --> 00:41:59.655
And, yes, so it's, yes, we might spend two hours on a call with an analyst talking to them about

00:41:59.655 --> 00:42:05.975
how they are using Python and the issues they're having, and what we make available that might

00:42:05.975 --> 00:42:08.375
make their lives easier. Right.

00:42:11.414 --> 00:42:16.215
Can you remind us the scale that we're talking about here as far as the number of end users

00:42:16.215 --> 00:42:19.495
who might be in one of those channels asking for help?

00:42:21.014 --> 00:42:25.335
There's, I think we're getting close to 600 analysts.

00:42:26.215 --> 00:42:34.294
Wow. That is a lot. And that's that blend of Python users and R users and all kinds of others.

