and we have about 10 minutes left together. So I have a couple of questions here. One will be

00:42:47.655 --> 00:42:54.775
a little bit more on the career advice end, so I'll save that until the end. It's Rachel's favorite

00:42:54.775 --> 00:42:59.335
question, the career advice question. We'd love to get that in. But I wanted to ask this anonymous

00:42:59.335 --> 00:43:05.735
one, which was, what was the change management process like from your experience, and how did

00:43:05.735 --> 00:43:11.894
you overcome organizational inertia when moving to Posit? Did you experience much pushback?

00:43:12.855 --> 00:43:17.494
Tom, were you at the organization when you actually adopted Posit first? You were not, right?

00:43:18.215 --> 00:43:26.134
No, I wasn't there when it was adopted. I've heard anecdotally that

00:43:26.775 --> 00:43:33.254
it, formerly the process wasn't, it, our process for adopting new things is,

00:43:34.454 --> 00:43:37.415
it's slow, but it does kind of rumble through.

00:43:39.814 --> 00:43:44.374
Getting new things is not that difficult as long as they're solving a completely new problem.

00:43:45.335 --> 00:43:46.775
Right. Yeah. We talked about that.

00:43:47.655 --> 00:43:56.934
I think my understanding is Posit came on during COVID when sort of emergency rules were a bit in

00:43:56.934 --> 00:44:01.894
effect. Right. But I don't know, I don't know the details. I wasn't working at the organization at

00:44:01.894 --> 00:44:10.215
the time. But yeah, I think it got in under the, that sort of, we have an urgent problem to solve.

00:44:10.454 --> 00:44:15.415
And we need to figure it out right now. We had, everybody in the world had that problem

00:44:15.415 --> 00:44:20.374
during this pandemic in so many different ways. I feel like that's why we're using Zoom right now,

00:44:20.374 --> 00:44:24.454
because all of a sudden everyone was like, oh, we now all need to work and not see each other.

00:44:25.574 --> 00:44:30.535
All right. Thank you so much, anonymous askers today. Yeah. And yeah, I'm sorry, I couldn't,

00:44:30.535 --> 00:44:34.694
oh, actually. Oh, go right ahead. I could say for our routine, for our more routine change. So

00:44:35.254 --> 00:44:43.175
not something big, like, oh, we'd like to adopt Posit, but for our change process for how we

00:44:43.175 --> 00:44:55.175
update the platform, it was a empathy pretty much. So I come at change management from a

00:44:55.175 --> 00:44:59.175
traditional I want to do thing, well, from an I want to do things background.

00:44:59.894 --> 00:45:05.095
And what are all these people doing who have forms for me? And it took a chunk of time to

00:45:05.095 --> 00:45:12.775
build empathy and trust between both us and the change management people that us understanding

00:45:13.335 --> 00:45:19.494
what their priorities are, what they're trying to do, and that actually their remit goes beyond

00:45:20.775 --> 00:45:25.095
protect the users, make sure there's not an outage. There's a lot more to it than that.

00:45:26.054 --> 00:45:31.814
To protect the users, make sure there's not an outage. There's also the coordinating

00:45:31.814 --> 00:45:37.494
wider business events where something we don't know about might depend on our system or

00:45:40.054 --> 00:45:46.054
something we depend on might be changing at the same time, thinking about risks, making sure all

00:45:46.054 --> 00:45:51.494
of the, you know, impact assessments and all of this stuff is in a sensible place.

00:45:52.134 --> 00:45:59.894
And also, yeah, just the bigger picture. We spent a long time talking with the change management,

00:45:59.894 --> 00:46:08.374
people, understanding, and also helping them understand what we do and that lots of the things

00:46:08.374 --> 00:46:15.735
that they are in a fairly paperwork state in their world, we're doing automatically

00:46:15.814 --> 00:46:21.975
automatically and showing them that actually we're ticking all the same boxes as you are,

00:46:21.975 --> 00:46:25.254
but we're doing it in a different way. How do we bring those together?

00:46:26.454 --> 00:46:33.415
And that was quite a long journey. But having gone through that, last time I went into the

00:46:33.415 --> 00:46:39.655
office, I got a hug from someone who was from the change team having not all of this done.

00:46:40.615 --> 00:46:44.775
And it's about relationships and empathy, pretty much.

00:46:46.694 --> 00:46:52.615
Yep. Every single time. I love that. Remember that the people you're working with are indeed

00:46:52.615 --> 00:46:58.855
human beings. Well, speaking of human beings, let's highlight some people from the chat here,

00:46:58.855 --> 00:47:06.454
because there was a question asked in Slido that I don't think is particularly a Tom question. I

00:47:06.454 --> 00:47:11.894
think this is much more of a community question. And sure enough, three different answers came in

00:47:11.894 --> 00:47:15.975
from the community, and I would love to read some of these. So the question was,

00:47:15.975 --> 00:47:21.655
sometimes it feels like only a few people on a team are stars who really move the needle.

00:47:21.655 --> 00:47:28.134
As a leader, how do you raise everyone's level so the whole team performs like your top players?

00:47:28.134 --> 00:47:33.574
What a good question. I'm going to read some of these answers that came in. And Tom, I will also

00:47:33.655 --> 00:47:39.014
ask you for input if you have any experience here. So one of them is, what I try to do is find the

00:47:39.014 --> 00:47:44.374
right task for the right person. If people enjoy what they're doing, they are more likely to

00:47:44.374 --> 00:47:50.054
perform at a high level. As an IC, this is the answer for me. Give me something that I enjoy

00:47:50.054 --> 00:47:54.054
doing, also something that's really in my wheelhouse and makes me feel comfortable and

00:47:54.054 --> 00:48:00.535
is in alignment with my values, and I'm going to do it much, much, you know, at a much higher level

00:48:00.535 --> 00:48:06.855
than I would otherwise. Another one is, you can also try pairing up the high performer with

00:48:06.855 --> 00:48:12.134
someone who is just learning, and they can level up that way. What a great suggestion. I also think

00:48:12.134 --> 00:48:17.175
that the higher level person will learn from the new person, because that sort of like feedback

00:48:17.175 --> 00:48:23.814
loop definitely happens. And then another one is, the tasks we get come from stakeholders.

00:48:23.814 --> 00:48:28.215
I've tried pairing, but this really doesn't move the needle and it's not scalable.

00:48:28.215 --> 00:48:35.014
I know my team of 10 can all perform super well, but only two are really meeting customer needs

00:48:35.014 --> 00:48:41.735
and are praised. I think that this is more of a question than an answer, but I think it might be

00:48:43.014 --> 00:48:46.374
an interesting one to tackle if you have any feedback or advice on it, Tom.

00:48:47.335 --> 00:48:52.454
I think something we try and do is we try and do things, particularly

00:48:54.934 --> 00:49:01.814
when it comes to externally facing, so other stakeholders within the business, we try and

00:49:03.254 --> 00:49:10.454
we try and act as a team doing these things, and we work in a way that all of us are comfortable with.

00:49:10.934 --> 00:49:16.215
I don't really like to think of it in terms of people being high or low performers. There's a

00:49:16.215 --> 00:49:22.934
set of work that needs to happen. People have got some specialisms and preferences, but the team

00:49:22.934 --> 00:49:30.134
as a unit is trying to get things done. There is a, I feel there's a bit of a risk if you've got

00:49:30.134 --> 00:49:37.415
too much of the kind of the hero culture type thing that can get you into a bad place.

00:49:37.494 --> 00:49:42.694
It's a bit of a downer for people who aren't being specifically called out. It's obviously

00:49:42.694 --> 00:49:51.254
good if it happens, but it feels like it shouldn't be especially routine. I particularly like it when

00:49:51.254 --> 00:49:57.735
we get praised as a team. Occasionally, we've had feedback from people where they are calling out

00:49:57.735 --> 00:50:05.574
the team as an entity who are delivering what people need, and I think that's a good thing.

00:50:06.134 --> 00:50:13.335
You can make sure people are doing the right work that suits them,

00:50:15.254 --> 00:50:20.134
but I'd also try and think in terms of is the team structured and is it receiving work in the

00:50:20.134 --> 00:50:30.295
right way that allows everybody the time, the space to succeed, and also the space to be doing

00:50:30.295 --> 00:50:37.975
things that aren't a strong suit so that they can learn from that. If you're running at 100%

00:50:37.975 --> 00:50:44.535
capacity all the time, you're in trouble as soon as someone's, you know, they're a bit under the

00:50:44.535 --> 00:50:54.535
weather or they're worried about something. If you're at that kind of capacity, it's going to be

00:50:54.535 --> 00:51:01.655
bad, and maybe to push back a little bit on it, try and have a slower pace of deadlines, or

00:51:03.175 --> 00:51:09.254
that kind of thing, but that also building trust with the wider organisation really helps with

00:51:09.254 --> 00:51:17.814
that. So, when we don't get do-it type requests, we get conversations about what's possible,

00:51:18.294 --> 00:51:25.975
how it might be doable, and we can start by having informal conversations that are a bit

00:51:25.975 --> 00:51:30.615
that's going to be easy, that's going to be hard. You can have that in a couple of weeks,

00:51:31.814 --> 00:51:38.135
and this will probably be eight months, and we have these kind of conversations.

00:51:38.135 --> 00:51:44.294
Sometimes people go, actually, it's not worth that much effort, and you're having honest

00:51:44.294 --> 00:51:51.015
conversations with stakeholders, and it's not kind of work flowing downhill, it's a collaboration,

00:51:51.814 --> 00:51:55.814
and some of the collaboration is actually sometimes it's going to take us a bit longer

00:51:55.814 --> 00:52:05.574
to do things, and it's a lot of trust-building to get to that point. We've done a huge chunk of that

00:52:06.774 --> 00:52:12.694
just by doing this for a long time, but that's, yeah, I think it's trying to avoid the situation

00:52:12.694 --> 00:52:16.934
is probably the way I would approach that. Well, I don't think I could have asked for a better piece

00:52:16.934 --> 00:52:23.654
of career advice there, because all of that is such a good idea, but so hard to actually

00:52:23.654 --> 00:52:30.694
implement, right? Like, stay at 85% capacity, allow yourself that buffer, build coalitions inside of

00:52:30.694 --> 00:52:35.654
your organisation, build trust, work on things collaboratively. Everything is a good idea until

00:52:35.654 --> 00:52:39.814
someone has to implement it, and it takes a long time. So, thank you so much for giving us all of your

00:52:39.814 --> 00:52:45.895
wisdom today. Darren, if you are there and can hear us still, we missed getting to talk to you.

00:52:45.895 --> 00:52:49.735
Hopefully, we'll talk to you again soon. So sorry you had connection issues. Tom, I hope you had a

00:52:49.735 --> 00:52:54.454
good time today. Thank you for joining us. Yeah, that was fun. Thanks for having me. Wonderful. Thank you

00:52:54.454 --> 00:53:00.294
for sharing all of HMRC's wisdom with us. We're so glad that you joined us today, everybody. I hope

00:53:00.294 --> 00:53:05.335
that you join us on the 3rd with Satish at Johnson & Johnson. Sign up for that webinar, come hang out

00:53:05.335 --> 00:53:10.934
with us then. And then next week, we're going to be joined by Samia Baig. I don't know how to say

